'''Koguchiyama Kofun''' (小口山古墳) is an ancient {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft}} located in Karisato, {{ill|Habikino|ja|羽曳野市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|12=draft}}, Japan. It is classified as a {{ill|circular tumulus|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=draft}} and is not designated as a historical site.

This tomb, from the {{ill|final Kofun period|ja|終末期古墳|1=Late Kofun tumuli|12=draft}}, contains a horizontal stone chamber carved from a single massive stone.

== Overview ==

The tomb is located 200 meters west of the {{ill|Minegazuka Kofun|ja|峯ヶ塚古墳|12=draft}}. It was discovered in 1912 during land clearing operations and introduced by {{ill|Kida Sadakichi|ja|喜田貞吉|12=draft}} as the "Hollowed Stone Coffin of Karisato in Kawachi." This site is significant in the history of archaeology. Excavations were conducted from 1979 to 1980 as part of the compilation of the {{ill|Habikino City History|ja|羽曳野市史|12=draft}}.

=== Kofun area ===

The mound is believed to be a circular tumulus with a diameter of 30 meters. To shape the mound, the natural terrain was cut away on the eastern and northern sides, forming a moat. The current mound height is 2.5 meters, but it is estimated to have originally been over 5 meters.

=== Horizontal Stone Chamber ===

[[File:Koguchiyama Kofun, 3D-P.jpg|thumb|300px|right|{{center|Perspective drawing of the stone chamber}}]]
[[File:Koguchiyama Kofun, 3D-N.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Diagram of the stone chamber}}]]
The burial facility is a horizontal stone chamber measuring 2.7 meters in length, 1.6 meters in width, and 1.6 meters in height. It was carved from a single block of white tuff from {{ill|Mount Nijō|ja|二上山|1=Futakami Mountain|2=ja|3=二上山|lt=Mount Futakami (or Nijo)|comment=Kanji are ambiguous between the two pronounciations|12=draft}}. The chamber opens to the south, with an interior depth of 2.13 meters, narrowing at the entrance to 0.87 meters and widening to 1.17 meters at the rear wall. The interior height is 0.63 meters.

The chamber’s outer shape is a rectangular box with a sloped roof resembling a {{ill|house-shaped sarcophagus|ja|家形石棺|1=House-shaped Sarcophagus|12=draft}}, although it lacks the characteristic rope-securing projections. It rests on three stone slabs (1.7 meters long, 1 meter wide, and 30 cm thick) arranged as a pedestal. Large natural stones of quartz and andesite are stacked along the east, north, and west sides for reinforcement, with the largest stone measuring 0.9 meters per side.

<gallery>
File:Koguchiyama Kofun, 3D-B.jpg|Overhead view of the stone chamber
File:Koguchiyama Kofun, entrance.jpg|Entrance to the stone chamber
File:Koguchiyama Kofun, sekkaku.jpg|Interior of the stone chamber
</gallery>

=== built ===

While no burial goods or artifacts were recovered to aid in dating, the chamber's style suggests it was constructed during the fourth quarter of the 7th century.

== References ==
* "Koguchiyama Kofun," in ''Habikino City History Volume 3, Historical Materials 1,'' 11. 436–440.

== See Also ==
